datasets.name: ALS Challenge Final
datasets.description_clean: Random Forest Based Solution to ALS Stratification Challenge Jinfeng Xiao Center for Biophysics and Quantitative Biology, The University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, USA This project has been made public as part of the challenge archive. Introduction My solutions to the sub-challenges 1 & 3 are based on random forest (R package randomForest^1^), and those to subchallenges 2 & 4 are based on survival random forest (R package randomForestSRC^2,3,4^). For sub-challenges 1 & 3, I used a home-made pipeline for feature selection, while for sub-challenges 2 & 4 the built-in importance function of the package was used to select features. Methods The followings are my steps to train models and make predictions. Here I would like to make it clear what I mean by writing "covariates" or "features". By "covariates" I refer to the variables, possibly longitudinal, given in the original data file. As we know the challenge rule requires me to first select 6 covariates from a whole bunch of them. By "features" I mean the information I extracted from the covariates and fed into machine learning algorithms. Details about how I did that will follow. Source codes and instructions to run them are given in the files part of this project. 1. Put together all data for each patient. The first thing I did was to read in and rearrange the training data of each sub-challenge into matrices. Each row contains the full information about a patient. Each entry contains the full information in the first 90 days about a covariate of that patient, formatted like this: FeatureValue1;FeatureDelta1;FeatureValue2;FeatureDelta2; ... . Then I dropped those features whose missing rate across training data is no less than 50%. 2. Encode covariants into features Since the random forest algorithm requires the same number of inputs (some of which may be imputed) from all patients in training data, the covariates and their delta values must be converted to some features that on one hand satisfy the requirement

datasets.name: VOC-ALS Database, VOiCe signals acquired in Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis Patients and Healthy Controls
datasets.description_clean: VOC-ALS is an available database of VOiCe signals acquired in healthy subjects and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) patients consecutively recruited at the ALS Clinic of the Federico II University Hospital of Naples, Italy. ALS is a neurodegenerative disease affecting motor neurons innervating muscles belonging to the bulbar, cervical, thoracic and lumbo-sacral region. Bulbar manifestation is a disabling condition that impairs patients' capacity to speech and swallow and is associated with reduced survival. Acoustic manifestations of speech disorders, such as dysarthria, are highly heterogeneous among patients, making their detection and classification a challenge for both clinical experts and automated systems. Main aim of this project is to provide researchers with an accessible and complete database on clinical and speech samples to enhance their studies in this field and to support the development of technologies to improve communicative interactions. Indeed, these technologies have the potential to answer crucial questions about the progression of speech impairments at each phase of ALS, enabling the identification of sensitive biomarkers for early diagnosis and accurate prognosis. This database consists of 1224 voice signals recorded from 153 italian-speakers participants: 102 ALS patients (65 males and 37 females) with different severity of dysarthria and 51 healthy subjects (32 males and 19 females). A smartphone application (Vox4Health) was used to record voices signals by performing two different tasks: the sustained phonation of the vowels /a/, /e/, /i/, /o/, /u/ and fast /pa/, /ta/, /ka/ syllable repetition. In addition, demographic information and detailed clinical profiles are provided for each participant to provide further information on how specific disease features are associated with basic derived speech metrics. When referencing this database, please cite: Dubbioso, R., Spisto, M., Verde, L., Iuzzolino, V. V., Senerchia, G., Salvatore, E., ...

datasets.name: GSE21536 Raw Data Layer from NCBI GEO
datasets.description_clean: Molecular cytogenetic techniques such as microarray analysis have allowed for a genotype-first approach to the characterization of chromosome abnormalities: in the absence of clinical features suggestive of a specific syndrome, patients with similar copy number imbalances can be examined for common clinical features. Using a genotype-first approach, we characterized microdeletions at 20q13.33 in six patients referred for genetic evaluation of developmental delay, mental retardation, and/or congenital anomalies. These deletions are relatively rare, with only 11 cases reported. A comparison to previously reported cases of 20q13.33 microdeletion shows phenotypic overlap, with clinical features that include mental retardation, developmental delay, speech and language deficits, seizures, and behavior problems such as autistic spectrum disorder. Based on analysis of the smallest region of overlap (SRO) among cases reported here and in previous studies, we discuss several possible candidate genes for specific clinical features, including ARFGAP1, CHRNA4, KCNQ2, and MYT1. Deletion of this region may play an important role in cognitive development.

In computer vision [1] and speech recognition [2,3] Deep Learning accomplishes better results than all other methods. Over the last years,new activation functions such as the rectified linear, the leaky rectified linear or the exponential linear functions have facilitated deep network training. Additionally, the use of newly discovered regularization techniques led to better performances. Deep neural networks are capable of learning hierarchical representations of the input, thus being able to process raw data without the need of a an expertise based feature extractor [6]. datasets.description_clean: OVERVIEW Recent advances in mobile health have demonstrated great potential to leverage sensor-based technologies for quantitative, remote monitoring of health and disease - particularly for diseases affecting motor function such as Parkinson’s disease. Such approaches have been rolled out using research-grade wearable sensors and, increasingly, through the use of smartphones and consumer wearables, such as smart watches and fitness trackers. These devices not only provide the ability to measure much more detailed disease phenotypes but also provide the ability to follow patients longitudinally with much higher frequency than is possible through clinical exams. However, the conversion of sensor-based data streams into digital biomarkers is complex and no methodological standards have yet evolved to guide this process.   Parkinson’s disease (PD) is a neurodegenerative disease that primarily affects the motor system but also exhibits other symptoms. Typical motor symptoms of the disease include tremors, slowness (bradykinesia), posture and walking perturbations, muscle rigidity and speech perturbations. In the clinic, symptoms are evaluated using physician observation and patient reports. datasets.description_clean: A Multi-Modal Dataset for Research on Automatic Dementia Detection This database is jointly collected and established by iFLYTEK Cogbrain Group and Shanghai Tongji Hospital, which contains digital speech and drawing data in a picture description task and a clock drawing test, to explore key linguistic and action features, and to further establish intelligent and convenient models for automatic dementia detection. All data were collected from 120 Chinese subjects (40 healthy control/40 Alzheimer's disease patients/40 mild cognitive ​​impairment subjects​). Any user accessing data must agree to: Not use the requested datasets, either alone or in concert with any other information, to identify or contact individual participants from whom data and/or samples were collected. Approved Users also agree not to generate and use information in a manner that could allow the identities of research participants to be readily ascertained. This dataset can only be used for research purposes and not for commercial use. If you are considering mirroring a copy of our publicly available datasets or providing direct access to any of our data via another tool or website need to refer to our article and indicate data source. The publicdata folder contains the following files: The data of each subject is saved in a separate folder. Every folder contains: the pictalking folder; the clock drawing folder; subject's psychological assessment data (.xlsx). Every file in the folder is named with the same encrypted string. 1 The pictalking folder: The folder contains the subject's audio data (.wav) and the manually transcribed text made with Praat Scripting software (.TextGrid) (1)Each wav file is a 16-bit mono speech signal with a 16k sample rate. (2)There are three parts in each textgrid file, representing three different layers: "内容层" means the content of the dialogue, "xmin" and "xmax" represent the start and end frames of the audio, and "text" represents the manually transcribed audio text.

datasets.description_clean: NTAP project Development of a Child Neurofibromatosis Type 1 Health Related Quality of Life Measure Initiative: Patient Reported Outcome (PRO)   Name: Nancy Swigonski, MD, MPH (Principal Investigator) Name: Kavitha Nutakki, MBBS, MPH (Project Manager) Contact Email: knutakki@iupui.edu Dates: 2-1-14 to 1-31-17 Tumor Focus: plexiform neurofibroma Disease Focus: Neurofibromatosis Type 1 (NF1) Application: Clinical Endpoint Tool   Goals of Project: To develop and test the feasibility, reliability and validity of the child self-report and parent proxy-report versions of the Pediatric Quality of Life InventoryTM (PedsQLTM) NF1 module.   Aims: To develop and test the measurement properties of the Pediatric Quality of Life InventoryTM (PedsQLTM) Neurofibromatosis Type 1 Module for pediatric patients ages 5-25 with NF1 from the perspectives of patients and parents.   Impact: The PedsQLTM NF1 Module Scales demonstrated acceptable to excellent measurement properties, and may be utilized as standardized metrics to assess NF1-specific symptoms and problems in clinical research and practice in children, adolescents, and young adults. datasets.description_clean: Dataset Documentation Summary: The ALL ALS Clinical Research Consortium is establishing research to collect a wide range of samples, clinical information and measurements from Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS) symptomatic, ALS gene carriers and control cohorts. This consortium is being funded by the National Institutes of Health/National Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke (NIH/NINDS) and managed by two clinical coordinating centers (CCC) at Barrow Neurological Institute and Massachusetts General Hospital. The clinical sites are distributed across the country, and led by a group of collaborative principal investigators. ASSESS ALL ALS is a prospective, observational cohort study enrolling individuals who are currently living with ALS (Symptomatic cohort) and individuals without ALS or known ALS gene mutations (Control cohort). Symptomatic cohort participants have options of both on-site and off-site/remote enrollment. The overarching goal of ASSESS ALL ALS is to prospectively collect, store and harmonize a large set of longitudinal data, which will be shared through the AMP ALS central portal, and biospecimens that will be linked to the clinical data for open science sharing with the research community. datasets.description_clean: Dataset Documentation Summary: PREVENT ALL ALS is a prospective, observational cohort study enrolling individuals at risk for carrying inherited genetic variants known to be causative for ALS. Standard on-site clinical outcome measures include a neurological examination, handheld dynamometry (HHD and vital capacity (VC) and electromyography (EMG). Data also includes Edinburgh Cognitive and Behavioral ALS Screen (ECAS) and the CDR Dementia Staging Instrument PLUS National Alzheimer’s Coordinating Center (NACC) Behavior and Language Domains (Multidomain Impairment Rating Scale (MIR). Additionally, regular digital data collection of self-reported electronic Patient Reported Outcomes (ePROs) and speech measures were collected. Biospecimens include plasma, serum, RNA, whole blood for generation of induced pluripotent stem cells (iPSCs) and DNA for whole genome sequencing, and cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) via lumbar puncture (LP). The overarching goal of PREVENT ALL ALS is to prospectively collect, store and harmonize a large set of longitudinal data, which will be shared through the AMP ALS central portal, and biospecimens that will be linked to the clinical data for open science sharing with the research community. Overall Design: PREVENT ALL ALS is a single observational study with an optional sub-study for genetic testing results. PREVENT ALL ALS enrolled individuals from genetic ALS families who are either known carriers for ALS causative genes or who have not had prior genetic testing. Participants have regular in person and remote visits for collection of longitudinal biofluid collection and selected clinical measures. Yes Background/Intro The core predictor for all sub-challenges are Random Forests (either classification or regression ones). The ICOS method, applied to all four subchallenges, is composed of the following steps: 1) Division of the training data into training and validation sets. 2) Application of our RGIFE iterative feature elimination method [1] to the training dataset to filter down as much as possible the number of features. 3) We cluster the training set using only the filtered features using either k-means or hierachical clustering (using the Ward method) and with a number of clusters ranging from 2 to 8. 4) The training set is divided into clusters. The first system is a novel application of deep models in biological problems and the second system is a well designed kernel machine for solving the Gene Essentiality problem. Introduction The last decade has witnessed a tremendous increase in the amount of available biological data. Different technologies for measuring genome, epigenome, transcriptome, proteome, metabolome, and microbiome in different organisms are producing huge amounts of high dimensional data every day. High dimensional data provides unprecedented challenges and opportunities to get a better understanding of biological systems. Biological data usually includes thousands and sometimes millions of features that are measured over a much lower number of samples. There are challenges in collecting and logging the NF patients’ symptoms due to the rarity of the disorder and the multiplicity of potential symptoms. datasets.description_clean: Building a Next Generation Model for Biomedical Research Validation of health sensors using online community registries and collaborative data interpretation The Patient Voice Analysis project is an effort to assess the severity and fluctuations in Parkinson's disease symptoms from voice recordings. PatientsLikeMe and Dr. Max Little have joined with Sage Bionetworks to collect data and initiate a crowd-sourced analysis. This project is a first in leveraging voice recordings, self-reported outcomes (PDRS) and demographic information from people with Parkinson’s disease to address the following question: >Can we predict the total PDRS score and/or PDRS sub-scores of people from their voice? Goals: 1. Prove that crowdsourcing approaches to collect voice recordings can be linked to self-reported outcomes and analyzed safely in a distributed competition to validate the use of health sensors in diagnostic and biomedical research. 2. Combine three methods that have each been established independently; a. Collecting validated patient-reported outcomes (PRO) through an online patient community (PatientsLikeMe) b. Mass collection of voice samples to characterize Parkinson’s disease (Parkinson’s Voice Initiative) c. Community-based, reproducible collaborative data analysis on Synapse (Sage Bionetworks) 3. datasets.description_clean: Cross cell-type transcription factor binding prediction using deep learning models Guanjue Xiang, Akshay Kakumanu, Divyanshi Srivastava, Naomi Yamada, Lila Rieber and Shaun Mahony Background: We used two very different approaches to tackle the “ENCODE-DREAM” challenge. Our first approach relies on the assumption that TF binding in a given cell type is determined by an unknown mixture of two types of genomic features: 1) features that represent invariant properties of the TF itself; and 2) features that represent cell-specific interactions with other regulatory actors. We used this approach to make submissions for the conference round of the challenge. While working on the conference round, we realized that finding cell-type specific features de novo using DNase-Seq and RNA-Seq datasets turned out to be harder than we anticipated. This resulted in the poor performance of our overall model. On closer examination of the challenge datasets, we realized that for a majority of cases the test cell-type was closely related to one of the train cell-type. This motivated us to try our second approach. Instead of training on all the cell-types, we reasoned that training an extensive deep learning model on the closest related cell-type would be more effective. Briefly, our model has two convolutional layers that feed-forward to an LSTM layer, which is in turn connected to a two class out-put layer (Figure 1). Patients often do not have the literacy nor the ability to access the full corpus of the research literature and to navigate and interpret data coming from various genetic and biomedical resources. Nevertheless, patients understand their symptoms very well, as well as their hard journey with neurofibromatosis (NF). There's a need for a centralized user-friendly knowledge base that can collate all the available knowledge on NF, which can help patients understand their disease when first diagnosed, and guide them through possible and developing symptoms throughout their life. datasets.name: Wearables for gait in Parkinson's Disease and age-matched controls (WearGait-PD)
datasets.description_clean: Background Algorithms are playing an increasingly vital role in medical devices. Understanding the impact of curating accessible datasets on algorithm development and evaluation, the FDA collaborated with the U.S. Department of Veterans Affairs (VA) and Johns Hopkins School of Medicine to establish this open-access dataset containing raw (unprocessed) inertial measurement unit (IMU) and sensorized insole data from 100 individuals with Parkinson’s Disease (PD) and 85 age-matched controls synchronized to a gait reference system. Frame-by-frame annotation of participant actions during gait and balance tasks was incorporated into the dataset using video cameras synchronized to all systems. To expand the utility of this dataset, all data are associated with demographic information and clinical evaluations (e.g., medications, DBS-status, MDS-UPDRS scores). This wearables dataset can serve as a tool to assess novel algorithms for deriving gait metrics through wearables, establish distributions and variability of wearable-derived gait metrics, and provide correlational information about clinical evaluations and wearable-derived gait metrics, among other things. This wiki brings together in a hyperlinked format everything needed to work with these data, including: description of the data collection procedures, data processing and alignment, annotation processes, and data quality control processes. Explore the links below for additional details regarding the data and processing approaches, how to access the data, publications using these data, and contact information. datasets.description_clean: https://psychencode.synapse.org https://staging.psychencode.synapse.org About the Portal Text ->The consortium brings together several multidisciplinary teams to work together to generate large-scale gene expression and regulatory data from human postmortem brains across several major psychiatric disorders and developmental stages. The collective PsychENCODE resource provides sets of individuals characterized by a single assay or more than one assay type. This multidimensional dataset enables multi-omics analyses and provides an enhanced framework of regulatory genomic elements associated with neuropsychiatric disorders. The PsychENCODE Portal was developed by Sage Bionetworks with support of the National Institute of Mental Health (NIMH) Grant U01MH116492 and is part of the Sage Platform. The Capstone Collection from Phase I merges large-scale brain sequencing data generated by individual PEC studies. The Capstone project uniformly processes these bulk and single-cell transcriptome, chromatin modification, and genotype data using standardized RNA sequencing (RNA-seq), chromatin immunoprecipitation with sequencing (ChIP-seq), and genotyping pipelines. Users can search regulatory elements and variant annotations from PsychENCODE and other public datasets to understand the biology of the human brain. The collective PsychENCODE resource provides sets of individuals characterized by a single assay or more than one assay type. This multidimensional dataset enables multi-omics analyses and provides an enhanced framework of regulatory genomic elements associated with neuropsychiatric disorders. The PsychENCODE Portal was developed by Sage Bionetworks with support of the National Institute of Mental Health (NIMH) Grant U01MH116492 and is part of the Sage Platform. The Capstone Collection from Phase I merges large-scale brain sequencing data generated by individual PEC studies. The Capstone project uniformly processes these bulk and single-cell transcriptome, chromatin modification, and genotype data using standardized RNA sequencing (RNA-seq), chromatin immunoprecipitation with sequencing (ChIP-seq), and genotyping pipelines. Explore Capstone Collection. PsychSCREEN PsychSCREEN is an interactive resource for exploring and visualizing epigenetic and gene expression data produced by the PsychENCODE Consortium. Users can search regulatory elements and variant annotations from PsychENCODE and other public datasets to understand the biology of the human brain. Data from fetal samples lend insight into the epigenetics of brain development, and users can compare tissue samples from individuals with psychiatric disorders against normal samples to prioritize disease-associated genes and variants.
